Stanford Psychology Climate Survey: 2018-2019

Lucy King

Read in data

Goal

The goal of the Psychology Department Climate Survey is provide the department with insights into feelings of inclusion and equality (or lack thereof) within the graduate student, postdoc, and research staff population. This information will inform efforts to cultivate an inclusive community that values diverse questions, viewpoints, approaches, and participant samples to foster ingenuity, challenge biases, and promote intellectual growth. Further, this information will inform possible actions to foster individual and collective wellbeing, which is requisite for academic success.

Method

In Summer 2019, graduate students, postdoctoral fellows, and research staff were emailed an online link to complete the Climate Survey (a PDF of the survey is available on the Psychology Graduate Students Google Drive in the “Climate Survey” folder).

The survey included questions about feelings of belonging uncertainty, stereotype threat (i.e., concerns about negative judgement due to identity), contextual threat (i.e., beliefs and experiences bias and discrimination), beliefs about collective action (i.e., beliefs that others value increasing inclusivity), and gender dynamics (i.e., concerns about issues surrounding gender identity and harassment). In addition, we collected information concerning participation in the Diversity Committee (i.e., past participation and interest). We asked minimal demographics questions to avoid identifiability within the relatively small sample, emphasizing that these questions were optional.

We received 60 response to the survey. We included optional questions about position in the department (graduate student, postdoc, research staff), gender identity (female, male, other/non-binary), and identity as an underrepresented minority. Among participants who responded, the majority (N = 27) were graduate students, followed by research staff (N = 11), and postdoctoral fellows (N = 7). In terms of gender, approximately twice as many participants identified as female (N = 30) compared to male (N = 16); no one identified as “other/non-binary.” Finally, 18 participants identified as an underrepresented minority.

When participants were asked about the frequency with which they wondered “maybe I don’t belong” in the Psychology Department and in academia generally, the modal response was “sometimes”. Indeed, fifty proportion of students endorsed “sometimes.”

When thinking about the Psychology Department, very few participants reported never feeling concerned about belonging (3%). Therefore, having at least some concerns about belonging is a typical experience in the department. When thinking about academia, no one reported “never” or “always” feeling concerned about belonging; one third of participants reported “frequently” feeling concerned.

Collective action

d0_gather_inclus <-
  d0 %>% 
  gather(Q, value, inclus_stud, inclus_fac)

count_inclus <-
  d0_gather_inclus %>% 
  count(Q, value) %>% 
  group_by(Q) %>% 
  mutate(
    proportion = n / sum(n)
  ) %>% 
  arrange(Q, desc(n)) %>% 
  ungroup()

count_inclus %>% 
  filter(!is.na(value)) %>% 
  mutate(
    value = factor(
      value,
      levels = c(
        "Strongly disagree", 
        "Disagree", 
        "Somewhat disagree", 
        "Neither agree nor disagree", 
        "Somewhat agree",
        "Agree",
        "Strongly agree"
      )
    ),
    Q = factor(
      Q,
      levels = c(
        "inclus_stud",
        "inclus_fac"
      ),
      labels = c(
        "Students",
        "Faculty"
      )
    )
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(value, proportion)) +
  geom_col() +
  hist_facet_theme +
  labs(
    x = "I believe that this group (students, faculty) wants\nto make the department more inclusive"
  ) +
  facet_grid(.~Q)

Issues and actions

Gender dynamics

count_gender_haras <-
  d0 %>% 
  count(gender_text, gender_haras) %>% 
  group_by(gender_text) %>% 
  mutate(
    proportion = n / sum(n)
  ) %>% 
  arrange(gender_text, desc(n)) %>% 
  ungroup()

count_gender_haras
## # A tibble: 12 x 4
##    gender_text gender_haras     n proportion
##    <chr>       <chr>        <int>      <dbl>
##  1 Female      A little        10     0.333 
##  2 Female      Not at all      10     0.333 
##  3 Female      Moderately       8     0.267 
##  4 Female      Extremely        1     0.0333
##  5 Female      Very             1     0.0333
##  6 Male        Not at all      11     0.688 
##  7 Male        A little         2     0.125 
##  8 Male        Moderately       2     0.125 
##  9 Male        Extremely        1     0.0625
## 10 No response <NA>            11     0.786 
## 11 No response Not at all       2     0.143 
## 12 No response A little         1     0.0714
count_gender_haras %>% 
  filter(!is.na(gender_haras)) %>% 
  mutate(
    gender_haras = factor(
      gender_haras,
      levels = c(
        "Not at all", 
        "A little", 
        "Moderately", 
        "Very", 
        "Extremely"
      )
    )
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(gender_haras, proportion)) +
  geom_col() +
  hist_facet_theme +
  labs(
    x = "Concerned about safety from sexual harassment/assault,\n including feeling safe in the building at night?"
  ) +
  facet_grid(.~gender_text)
